      <article about="" typeof="schema:ScholarlyArticle">
        <h1 property="schema:name">Linked Research</h1>

        <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
          <blockquote>
            <p>You never change things by fighting the existing reality. To change something, build a new model that makes the existing model obsolete.</p>
            <footer>Attributed to <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buckminster_Fuller">Buckminster Fuller</a></cite>.</footer>
          </blockquote>

          <p>The concepts and ideas discussed so far cover various aspects of the scholarly communication ecosystem, and in many cases ideas from different sources and different times overlap. I now take this related work, along with the context of the modern Web and the current state of scholarly communication, and use these to formulate the <cite><a href="https://linkedresearch.org/">Linked Research</a></cite> (<abbr title="Linked Research">LR</abbr>) initiative. This comprises foremost a set of principles intended to describe a researcher-centric information and interaction space optimised for scholarly communication on the Web. I will refer and reflect on these principles for the other contributions of this thesis.</p>

          <p>It quickly becomes clear that these principles build on existing ideas, but also in many cases are developed further and push for a future free from the constraints of academic publishing models tied to media from the past, as well as a strive to enable content creators to exercise their creativity to the fullest extent possible in order to affectively communicate.</p>

          <p>LR is also set up as a community effort, and here I present a snapshot of work which is expected to continue to develop as others contribute and more diverse voices bring their requirements to the table. For now, I acknowledge the bias towards Western (Euro and US centric) academic practices in the domain of Computer Science. However, the initiative is discipline-agnostic.</p>

<p>Mention domain+hosting costs</p>

          <section id="realising-social-changes" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#realising-social-changes">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Realising Social Changes</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>This section is about how we realise/enable the social changes technically, whilst still adhering to the LR principles (ie. why we can't just use twitter/easychair for academia etc).</p>
              <p>Point at the social parts of the Control Yourself chapter (AP, AS2, LDN) and say how these fit into the ecosystem. How they mean we can do the things people need to do in scholarly communications in a way that meets the principles.</p>
              <p>This is where we bring the decentralisation stuff back home to in-practice scholarly comms.</p>

              <p>There are different approaches to 'fixing' the ecosystem. We could try a wholehearted replacement of the current system. That's unlikely to succeed. We could try to directly change existing players (like publishers, conferences) and demand that they do things differently. Also probably not gonna happen. It might be better to work *alongside* existing practices, and gradually ease scholars into new ways of operating. our goal is not necessarily to replicate major academic publishing houses or academic social networks..  smaller, personalised connected components might be both easier to realise and more effective in the long run. But.. who knows.</p>

