          <section id="discussion" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#discussion">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Discussion</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>The Web is the <strong>medium</strong> in which <cite>Linked Research</cite> is a <strong>message</strong> within.</p>

              <p class="todo">Move some of this to framing/background</p>

              <p>The Web is capable of offering rich interactions for humans and machines. While scientists have adopted the Web as an ideal medium to exchange knowledge, I posit that it is not being used efficiently or optimally due to both social and technical reasons. What we can ask is if it is possible to use the medium to its full potential, and observe the <em>effects</em>. We can also consider the consequences of pushing this to the extreme - as per McLuhan's <em>reverses into</em>. Hence we should strive to understand the ways we are self-amputating in the pursuit of acquiring knowledge about the fabric of reality. LR is not only a set of design principles to shape the technical scholarly communication ecosystem, but an initiative to strive to experience the full effects of the Web by adopting what it has to offer. In part, LR is an attempt to actively break away from practices which enhance isolationism or still fundamentally work within the print-centric paradigm. Technologies that enable or enhance the social dimensions on the Web for example makes involvement with content possible. The design principles are a nudge towards this goal.</p>

              <p>LR is also a conceptual framework that describes how implementations in scholarly communication can interoperate. Its philosophy is influenced by the social machinery to build a knowledge Web for humans and machines as part of a cooperating system. Knowledge tends to get lost if it can't be retrieved, hence it has limited value. Thus, a holistic approach to universal access for all agents is an important criteria.</p>

              <p>LR's design is aligned with certain qualities of existing works and practices in the wild. However, LR looks at the problem space by revisiting the characteristics of the medium, and what the actors can achieve in context of scientific communication. Arbitrary or artificial barriers are considered to be anti-patterns.</p>

              <p>Are there ideological and technology traps? The traps can be seen as analogous to McLuhan's <q>reverses into</q> effect. When the LR design principles are pushed to the extreme, highly specialised and fine-grained centralised systems can and will emerge while still operating within the larger decentralised system on the Web. The degree of federation or interoperability among the autonomous systems will vary. The effects may be that of a new generation of third-party control and authority over certain information spaces. For example, just as centralised publishing and distribution services currently exist for the dominating paper-centric industry, the medium can still accommodate similar control over semantic and granular scientific resources. It is worthwhile to note that the ecosystem would only become more diverse as it expands. Entropy is an inherent property of the Web.</p>

              <p>It is worthwhile to note here that the earlier or existing models for information exchange that has been described so far primarily focus on institutional or subject repository driven scholarly communication. They are contrasted against the involvement of third-party (for-profit) service providers which impose a particular arrangement of the coupling of the scholarly information space per <em>forces and functions</em>. In the remainder of this thesis, I focus on enabling a <strong>researcher-centric</strong> model; whilst this can be situated within the same <q>deconstructing</q> or <q>decoupling</q> school of thought, its pursuit is embracing greater control by content creators through the native characteristics of the Web, without interfering with the certification function regardless of the academic discipline; humanities, social, natural, formal, or applied sciences. The notion of content creators or consumers having some control on accessibility, registration and archiving, inherits certain qualities of coupling. That is, researcher-centric coupling unleashes the potentials of expressivity and effective scholarly communication.</p>

              <p>While the criteria for publishing provided by <cite>Genuine Semantic Publishing</cite> is valuable and can also be exercised by following LR's <q>interpretable</q> design principle, we do not prescribe it in order to not conflict with the <q>freedom of expression</q> principle. If a third-party imposes a specific way to express knowledge, whether it is through file formats and their structure and semantics; what (meta)data to include or not include; or inclusion and use of interactive components; the quality of the communication is subject to be less effective because the author may have to make compromises. Information loss occurs and communication quality naturally degrades simply because what the actors wish to convey in their message, and how, will have to be filtered down in order to fit the requirements of a third-party, data formats, or user interfaces.</p>

              <p>At the time of this writing, LR's principles and the strive for interoperable systems is conceived within the Web paradigm, as opposed to the broader Internet. There are emerging technologies and platforms within the Internet which are highly specialised for security, versioning, distributed, and so forth, which give way to new possibilities on how the scholarly communication market can be realised. While this thesis fits LR's principles into particular contemporary technology stacks, this is for practical purposes and to demonstrate what can be achieved today. Nothing prevents the principles from being adopted under different environments. It is quite likely that the design philosophies of the new environments will differ.</p>

              <p class="todo">What is the scope? What are some of the instabilities or inadequate use of the system? What is missing or could use more development/attentions?</p>

              <p class="todo">We all produce and distribute information. It is our part of our nature. What kinds of rules would serve everyone's (writers and readers) needs in the Web environment? What may be the constrains?</p>

              <p class="todo">Use Kuhn's "accuracy consistency scope simplicity fruitfulness" to explain the quality of the LR paradigm,</p>


              <p>LR does not deconstruct scholarly publishing, but that it ironically indicates instead the need for a counter-environment as a means of practising the dominant and unnoticed environment.</p>


              <p>Sooner or later we need a strategy to address questions like: <em>What do we aim to accomplish?</em> <em>Who is trying to do it and for the benefit of whom?</em> <em>How do we know whether we are making progress and when we have succeeded?</em></p>

              <p>Potential solutions to these questions and new challenges need to address the connection and the gap between researchers, academic and public institutions, as well as what ends up in the commons. It is not just about researchers making their contributions available on the Web, or about conferences requesting semantically annotated contributions, or operating with transparent peer-review. All of these things must move in combination. Some of the kinds of actors in the ecosystem to address fulfilling the the LR principles can be along these lines:</p>

              <dl>
                <dt id="cooperating-researchers">Researchers</dt>
                <dd>Researchers take full responsibility of their contributions. This can be at any Webspace they put trust on or have sufficient authority over, eg. personal site, institutions’ student and faculty pages. Making their work as <q>Webby</q> as possible eg. linking their arguments and citations to others', interactive story-telling or experimentation possibilities for their readers to be learnable. Researchers can take special care to ensure URI persistence and archiving of their work.</dd>

                <dt id="cooperating-conferences-and-journals">Conferences and Journals</dt>
                <dd>In person conferences and online journals should encourage and accept research publications which use native Web standards and technologies. Support transparent and attributed peer-review process. Aggregation or proceedings of the events can be machine-friendly and archival measures should be taken in addition to those of researchers.</dd>

                <dt id="cooperating-public-institutions">Public Institutions</dt>
                <dd>Given sufficient evidence of the Web Science community’s acknowledgement of research as well as its contributions, eg. peer-reviews, academic institutions can officially acknowledge such work towards academic credit. Libraries can  make the community’s output discoverable, catalogued, enriched, among many other things.</dd>
              </dl>

              <p>Mention https://communitywiki.org/wiki/DoOcracy https://web.archive.org/web/20181231115548/https://communitywiki.org/wiki/DoOcracy ?</p>
            </div>
          </section>
        </div>
      </article>
    </main>
